Name: taskbarOverlayIcon

Type: property

Syntax: set the taskbarOverlayIcon of <stack> to <iconPath>

Summary:
Displays a small overlay icon in the corner of a stack's Windows taskbar button.

Associations: stack

Introduced: 1.0.0

OS: windows

Platforms: desktop

Example:
-- Show a notification badge icon when new messages arrive
set the taskbarOverlayIcon of this stack to specialFolderPath("resources") & "/badge-mail.ico"

Example:
-- Clear the overlay when messages have been read
set the taskbarOverlayIcon of this stack to empty

Parameters:
stack:
A reference to a stack, or an expression that evaluates to a stack.

iconPath:
The full path to an .ico file to display as the overlay.
Pass empty to remove any existing overlay icon.

Value:
The <taskbarOverlayIcon> of a stack returns the path most recently set.
The default value is empty.

Description:
Use the <taskbarOverlayIcon> property to draw a small badge icon over the
lower-right corner of a stack's Windows taskbar button. This is the same
mechanism used by email clients and messaging apps to signal unread items
or status changes without requiring the user to bring the window forward.

The overlay is drawn at 16×16 pixels by Windows, regardless of the icon
file's nominal size. For the sharpest result, supply an .ico file that
includes a 16×16 frame alongside any larger sizes.

Setting <taskbarOverlayIcon> to empty removes the overlay immediately.

If the path refers to a file that does not exist or cannot be loaded as
an icon, the call silently has no effect.

>*Note:* The <taskbarOverlayIcon> property only has a visual effect on
> Windows. On macOS and Linux the property is accepted without error
> but has no effect.

>*Note:* The <taskbarOverlayIcon> property is not persistent — it is not
> saved into the stack file. Set it in a `preOpenStack` or `startUp`
> handler each time the application launches.

>*Note:* Windows reads the overlay icon at the moment
> <taskbarOverlayIcon> is set. You can safely delete or replace the .ico
> file afterwards without affecting the currently displayed overlay.

References: taskbarProgress (property), jumpListTasks (property)

Tags: windowing
